ing of—and challenges to—modern property regimes have shaped urban policy and politics. Drawing on critical geographical theory and community-based ethnography, Safransky shows how private property functions as a racialized construct, an ideology, and a moral force that shapes selves and worlds. By thinking the city “after property,” Safransky illuminates alternative ways of imagining and organizing urban life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxSocial conditionsy21st century2DLC. 0aAfrican AmericanszMichiganzDetroitxSocial conditionsy21stcentury. 0aHousingxAbandonmentzMichiganzDetroit2DLC. 0aHousingxAbandonmentzMichiganzDetroit. 0aPropertyxSocial aspectszUnited States2DLC. 0aRight of propertyzUnited States2DLC. 0aSociology, UrbanzMichiganzDetroit2DLC. 0aSociology, UrbanzMichiganzDetroit. 0aUrban policyzMichiganzDetroit2DLC. 0aUrban policyzMichiganzDetroit. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024613?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024613/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englis